.963 0.9795 0.9981\n       KDE     0.970 0.9835 0.9978\nStratified     0.969 0.9829 0.9978\n       KMM     0.934 0.9628 0.9975\n","output_type":"stream"},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":"<Figure size 1950x650 with 3 Axes>","image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":19},{"id":"2f03ba30","cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n# 📊 Part 3 — Classical ML: Breast Cancer Wisconsin\n\n**Dataset:** `load_breast_cancer()` — 569 samples, 30 continuous features,\nbinary classification (malignant vs benign).\n\n**Shift mechanism:**  \nTraining is biased toward **large-radius tumour** samples (feature `mean_radius` \nabove the 40th percentile).  The test set is a balanced random hold-out,\ncontaining a much higher proportion of small-radius cases than training.\n\nThis mimics a clinical ML scenario where early data collection focused on\nsevere/advanced cases, but the deployed model must handle the full patient spectrum.","metadata":{}},{"id":"e92b9fb3","cell_type":"code","source":"# ── 1. Load & create shift ────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nbc          = load_breast_cancer()\nX_bc, y_bc  = bc.data.astype(float), bc.target       # 569 x 30\n\nnp.random.seed(42)\nradius      = X_bc[:, 0]                              # feature 0 = mean radius\nr_thresh    = np.percentile(radius, 40)               # 40th percentile\n\nhi_r = np.where(radius >= r_thresh)[0]\nlo_r = np.where(radius <  r_thresh)[0]\n\nn_train_ml  = 350\nn_tr_hi     = int(0.78 * n_train_ml)\nn_tr_lo     = n_train_ml - n_tr_hi\n\ntr_hi       = np.random.choice(hi_r, n_tr_hi, replace=False)\ntr_lo       = np.random.choice(lo_r, n_tr_lo, replace=False)\ntrain_idx   = np.concatenate([tr_hi, tr_lo])\ntest_idx    = np.setdiff1d(np.arange(len(X_bc)), train_idx)\n\nX_tr_b, y_tr_b = X_bc[train_idx], y_bc[train_idx]\nX_te_b, y_te_b = X_bc[test_idx],  y_bc[test_idx]\n\n# Oracle: balanced random split\nor_idx         = np.random.choice(np.arange(len(X_bc)), n_train_ml, replace=False)\