E is competitive but dimension-limited** | Very effective in low-dim spaces (≤5 PCA components); degrades in high dimensions. Best for CV tasks or low-feature-count ML. |\n| **KMM provides the best theoretical guarantees** | Minimises MMD directly; benefits from PCA pre-processing for speed. Preferred when you have budget for QP optimisation. |\n| **Stratified Resampling is the simplest** | No density estimation; just histogram matching on the first PC. Surprisingly effective and easy to audit. Good baseline correction method. |\n| **Always check the overlap condition** | All methods fail when P_train and P_test have disjoint support. Visualise PCA projections first; if they don't overlap, collect more data. |\n| **Validate on the target distribution** | Use test-distribution samples in your validation set — evaluating on a random split from a biased pool gives false confidence. |\n\n### 🔑 Rule of thumb\n```\n1. Detect shift  →  train a domain classifier; if AUC >> 0.5, shift is present\n2. Quick fix     →  DIW (3 lines of code, works everywhere)\n3. High stakes   →  KMM (QP) on PCA-projected features\n4. Production    →  continuous monitoring + periodic re-calibration\n```","metadata":{}}]}